   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_XXXX_1817_05_23_page01.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                  <name type="place" ref="Id_where"/>
                  <date when="1816-08-04"/>August 4, 1816. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  <persName>
                     <!-- Use if letter has a saluation ("Dear Sir," for example). If not, delete this line.-->
                  </persName>
               </salute>
            </opener>
             <p><note><hi rend="underline">Copy of R L E's letter to Hunter</hi></note>
                 Dear Sir <add>Some</add> <title ref="./Workography.xml#Comic1">Comic Dramas</title> <del>sometimes</del> inculcate<lb/>
                 useful lessons - for instance <hi rend="underline">"Three weeks after<lb/>
                     marriage"</hi> pointed out to me so strongly the folly<lb/>
                 of explanations and recriminations that I have<lb/>
                 avoided them not only with my wife but<lb/>
                 with my friends - I shall therefore say no<lb/>
                 more about your misapprehension with <choice><orig>res-<lb/>
                     -pect</orig><reg>respect</reg></choice> to the time of your publishing <title ref="./Workography.xml#Ormon1">Ormond</title><lb/>
                 except to point out that I from time <add>to time</add> told you<lb/>
                 the manuscript would be shortly sent to you<lb/>
                 And that I distinctly told you that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> had<lb/>
                 written 1200 pages in three months. Could it be<lb/>
                 supposed she worked so hard, deprived herself<lb/>
                 of all amusement and hazarded her health<lb/>
                 for the purpose of having a manuscript in <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BriaX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.<lb/>
                     Briars</persName> hands for six months before it was to be<lb/>
                 published?<lb/></p>
               
             <p>We are however perfectly satisfied that this<lb/>
                 was only a dull misapprehension on your<lb/>
                 part and that you did not mean to treat<lb/>
                 <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> as a hireling. We entirely accede<lb/>
                 to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Captain Beauforts</persName> arrangements -viz - that<lb/>
                 the printer shall work double tides. Indeed it<lb/>
                 will be as much your interest as it is our<lb/>
                 pleasure that you should hasten the printing<lb/></p>
               
             <p>I shall now answer your former letter<lb/>
                 relative to our money transactions.<lb/>
                 In the first place I reiterate for the third time <add>my </add> <unclear>request</unclear><lb/>
                 that the small account which exists between us<lb/>
                 may be sent to use - We have ordered books and <choice><orig>var-<lb/>
                   rious</orig><reg>various</reg></choice> articles and these small matter should not
                 be<lb/>
               
               mixed with a large account.<lb/></p>
             
             <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_XXXX_1817_05_23_page02.jpg"/>  
             
             <p> <hi rend="underline">Secondly</hi> the time of payment of <title ref="./Workography.xml#Comic1">Comic Dramas</title> not<lb/>
                 having been mentioned between us we shall state to<lb/>
                 be the seventh of next may - being a year after <choice><orig>pub-<lb/>
                     -lication</orig><reg>publication</reg></choice><lb/></p>
               
             <p><hi rend="underline">Thirdl</hi> - With respect to the three volumes of tales<lb/>
                 I propose that one third should be paid at the <choice><orig>expi-<lb/>
                     -ration</orig><reg>expiration</reg></choice> of six months after its publication - Another<lb/>
                 third at the expiration of a year - and the <choice><orig>remain<lb/>
                     -der</orig><reg>remainder</reg></choice> at the expiration of a year and a half -<lb/>
                 I think these payments will press more lightly upon<lb/>
                 you than the disbursement of a large sum at one<lb/>
                 time. But if you prefer paying the whole at the end<lb/>
                 of one year we shall most willingly agree to that <choice><orig>ar-<lb/>
                     rangement.<reg>arrangement</reg></orig></choice><lb/></p>
               
             <p>    <hi rend="underline">Fourthly</hi> I will defray the expense of cancelling the<lb/>
                 two sheet <unclear></unclear> Harrington which were at my <unclear>desire</unclear><lb/>
                 improvi<unclear>de</unclear>ntly cut off from the first volume<lb/></p>
               
             <p>      <hi rend="underline">Fifthly</hi> We desire that ten guineas may be given<lb/>
                 to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#ChurX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Churchill</persName> when the tales are finished.<lb/></p>
          <p>     
              We thank you for your handsome &amp;<lb/>
              manly letter. And I do assure you that I am as<lb/>
              little disposed to take offence, as you can be to give it<lb/></p>
            <closer>
                I am dear Sir, your Obed<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Servant<lb/>
                <persName ref="./EdgeR1">R. L. Edgeworth</persName><lb/> -<!--include linebreaks, if used. example: <closer> Yours<lb/> Very sincerely<lb/> -->
            </closer>
            <postscript>
                <p>You have not sent us <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WebbS1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Webbe's</persName> music<lb/></p>
                  
                <p>And now my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> accept<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria's</persName> own heartfelt thanks - you have by the<lb/>
                    admirably able hand &amp; successful manner in<lb/>
                    which you have managed this business relieved<lb/>
                    me from a state of anxiety which I can describe to<lb/>
                    you only by saying that <hi rend="underline">you have taken my mind<lb/>
                        off the rack</hi> - And now I feel &amp; thank you for the<lb/>
                    delight of seeing my father perfectly satisfied &amp; happy<lb/>
                    &amp; all smooth again with poor Hunter - my father<lb/>
             <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_XXXX_1817_05_23_page03.jpg"/>     
                    when I requested to add a line from myself to his letter<lb/>
                    to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunter</persName> desired that I should not do so. - Indeed I <choice><orig>for-<lb/>
                        bear</orig><reg>forbear</reg></choice> with the less reluctance because I am so convinced<lb/>
                    of the mischief I have done &amp; the misapprehension I<lb/>
                    created in <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HuntX1">Hunters</persName> mind by the foolish note I wrote<lb/>
                    about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HarrX1">Harrington</persName> - However good the intentions with<lb/>
                    which it was written it has I see done mischief and<lb/>
                    I will interfere no more - You may conceive what<lb/>
                    I should have suffered if I had been the cause of a total<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">break up</hi> with a person who was doing all he could<lb/>
                    to oblige me - From this you have saved me &amp; I<lb/>
                    leave it to you to judge how much I feel obliged<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personograph.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/></p>
               
                <p>  My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> after all the Compliments you have received<lb/>
                    from these distinguished authors what can my mite of praise be<lb/>
                    worth - ? But I must have the satisfaction of saying that you have<lb/>
                    managed the Hunterian controversy <hi rend="underline">perfectly</hi>- and that you have done the<lb/>
                    very thing I not only wished but expected. Telling dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">Alicia</persName> that<lb/>
                    she shall hear from me by the twopenny post - and in the mean time<lb/>
                    thank her for her very cheerful and pleasant letter and give her my love<lb/>
                    Your <title ref="./Workography.xml#Karam1">Karamania</title> is beautifull - tho' the plates are not as delicate as on the Indian paper F E.<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria</persName> is quite charmed with what<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauA1">Alicia</persName> says of the little dramas - it is<lb/>
                    just what she wished but did not dare<lb/>
                    to hope to hear from her readers - We<lb/>
                    are all curious to know which is liked<lb/>
                    by who - which by she &amp; which by you<!--A postscript goes here, outside the <closer>. --><lb/></p>
            </postscript>
            <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
            <!-- Format for postscripts. 
               Postscripts do NOT go inside closer tags. Adjust to take into account the order in your letter. 
               Sometimes the signature is on page three, the address on page four, then the postscript follows back on the top of page one, for example.-->
            <closer><!--Use the <closer> element again to hold Address Leaf information.-->
               <address>
                   <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Captain Beaufort</persName> <addrLine/>
                  31 Harley Street<addrLine/>
                  London<addrLine/>
                  Hunter<addrLine/>
                  [unclear][/unclear]MY 23<addrLine/>
                  1817<addrLine/>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
